    I'm designing a 3d game so I know your problem.  I didn't come up with a
clean solution, but I can up with a way of doing it.  I might have a better
solution for you if you told me what this was for and what it is supposed to
do for you.  (Such as a light reflection equation, a "laser to hit" equation,
having a ship find and move towards it's target, etc.)
    In anycase, the easiest way to solve for something like this is to make
the line AB fall on a axis.  I know in real world terms, that isn't going to
happen, so "make" it happen by moving it (transforming it) and rotating until
it does.  Taking points C & D with it.  At that point, it is elementary to
solve the D rotation issue (meaning how many degrees off the plane it is).


    In detail it would work like this (Keep in mind do all these things to all
the points at the same time so they are still in realitive position to each
other):

Note: I'm using @ as Theta(angle)

1. Translate A so that it becomes 0,0,0
2. Rotate B along the Y axis so it's X coordinate becomes 0 (
B@=ArcCos(Bx/sqrt(Bx^2+Bz^2)) )
3. Rotate B along the X axis so it's Y coordinate becomes 0 (
B@=ArcCos(Bz/sqrt(Bz^2+By^2)) ).  Bz at this point will be it's length since
it is now running straight down the Z axis).
4. Get the Angle of C along the Z axis ( C@=ArcCos(Cx/sqrt(Cx^2+Cy^2)) ).  Do
the same for D using the same equation ( D@=ArcCos(Dx/sqrt(Dx^2+Dy^2)) ).
5. Since you now have both angles, simple subtract @C-@D.  If the result is
greater than 90 degrees, then you should subtract 180 from it.  (ie. if
@C-@D=120 degrees, then 120-180=-60 so you would have to rotate D -60 degrees
to get to the closest intersection of the plane defined by ABC).


    I must repeat that each thing you do to one point above you must do to the
rest to keep their respective position when doing the translation or rotation. 
This shouldn't be a problem for your rotation function.  I wish I had a
direction equation for you, but I don't have one.  I'm using simular types of
solutions in my code because I don't have a better equation for the purpose
that i need.  If done right, it really isn't bad for performance.  Hope this
helps!




