It's our choice to show to everyone that we *WANT* the OS development
go on. If 3.5 fails, then it's over (seriously, it will be *really* over,
as I know that some serious companies would probably stop doing AMIGA
stuff, if no perspectives in OS development are visible anymore). If 3.5
succeeds, then there is a good chance that we will see more updates
in future, which might bring more revolutionary changes than 3.5 did.
3.5 is the first step, which should be followed by more steps. And
besides that people claiming that 3.5 is only a collection of patches
have definitely no clou about what is going on, and they certainly
did not buy the OS update and read all the change logs (which takes
quite some time to read). The price of 3.5 corresponds to the amount
of time needed by all those people to do their work (check the 3.5
web pages for a list of all developers). I think we all agree that
OS development only makes sense, if finally some money is coming back
(with the exception of projects like Linux where those people are doing
it just for fun). I find it also funny that people say that 3.5 is too
expensive but at the same time happily would spend 10x this amount for
new hardware even at a time when nobody knows what will run on the
hardware and what won't. And don't forget that hardware can't be pirated,
while software can indeed, so where is the risk, at the hardware or
software development company? I guess that quite some people are first
spending huge amount of money for new hardware and afterwards don't
have enough left to buy software, hence they pirate the software and
say that they have already spent 'enough' money to use new AMIGA
hardware/software technologies.

People which don't support 3.5 or pirate 3.5 are not helping the AMIGA
but doing the opposite. And people buying hardware before the software
situation has been resolved are doing a mistake. Hardware without
software is useless. At the moment the situation around the new PPC
boards in conjunction with Amiga-OS is completely unclear, so all
people which are seriously interested to continue to use Amiga-OS
are good off to wait and keep their existing hardware until the
situation has been resolved. All other people not interested in
Amiga-OS are invited to do whatever they like, for example starting
to write/use QNX/Linux software.

