@node 07989.008
Subject: Wipeout2097
From: Sam Jordan <sam_jordan@spin.ch>
Date: Tue, 16 Nov 1999 19:26:39 +0200

Hi

As you probably know, Wipeout2097 is already out, so that people
which preordered the game should either already have got the game
or will get the game very soon. Those people coming to cologne also
had the possibility to buy the game.

I just would like to point out to some problems there are and how
these can be fixed. Please, if you see people having problems in
newsgroups or elsewhere try to help them by passing my infos to them.


The first problem is, that quite some people experience a PPC crash
at startup, before the first picture appears. Even I myself had the
crash at cologne at the beginning, luckily we found the reason there.
It turned out that the installed Warp3D main library was too old, so
that we had to install the Warp3D archive which is on the WO2097 CD.
Unfortunately the installer didn't copy the new library, so that we
did it by hand. The reason is probably, that the version number
of the main library wasn't raised by accident, while the version number
of the Permedia2 driver was raised indeed. So the driver reported
'chroma test available' and the game then wanted to jump to a API
function which wasn't present in older Warp3D main libraries.

All people having the same problem should first remove their Warp3D
installation (IMHO deleting Warp3DPPC.library should be enough) and do
a fresh installation of Warp3D from the WO2097 CD.


Somebody else wrote that he fixed a crash by replacing the existing
powerpc.library by the on on the WO2097 CD. This is double strange,
as the version on CD should be the latest one, but according to this
people it isn't. I didn't put the WarpUp archive myself on the CD
therefore I don't know it (and I didn't get a production CD yet).
Again, if anyone has done similar experiences, please let me know.


The third problem is about playing CD audio tracks. It seems to work
fine with SCSI drives, unfortunately not with at leasst some IDE drives
yet. The problem will be worked on in future and if a solution is found
a patch will be released. If anyone with IDE drive manages to play the
CD audio tracks using WO2097 please let me know, so that we get some
information which drives are affected.


Finally after these problem description I just would like to point out,
that the people visiting the fair at cologne were very impressed about
the game, its graphics quality and performance. When I asked people to
estimate the resolution which was set during the game, most people assumed
a resolution around 800*600*16, although the game itself was running
most of the time at 480*384*16. Which impressively shows that plain numbers
aren't worth anything compared to the visual experience.

bye
