@node 07991.014
Subject: Re: Re: Shogo- and Heretic2-demos
From: "Andrew Korn" <andrew.korn@lineone.net>
Date: Wed, 17 Nov 1999 22:58:10 -0000

 Sinan Gurkan said:

> If I were you, I would release the demo before the full version is out...
> I`m sure it`ll get more pre-orders if people see the demo first...

In principle I totally agree, I know for a fact that a lot of people will
simply not buy a game until they have seen a demo. In practise it's not so
simple. Amiga games development just ain't like PC game development. 

Recently we've seen a few PC companies breaking the mould with thoroughly
pre-release demos (notably UT and Q3a), however normally a demo is not
produced until after the game is basically done. However, there tends to be a
greater lead-in time for a PC game than an Amiga game. It's normal for a PC
publisher to spend a lot more time on play testing, QA assessment, packaging
design and pre-sales marketing than Amiga publishers do, largely as a matter
of scale. A tiny Amiga games developer/publisher tends to be desperate to get
their product out and start working on the next one, while a large PC
publisher will ususally have enough titles that they can afford to stagger
launches. You'll find that demos of games from smaller & indie PC developers,
or games that have been delivered late frequently come out after the on sale
date, too. 

I'd really like to see a little more lead-in on Amiga games. It's
understandable why this doesn't take place, but there does tend to be a lack
of time given to the final polish stages. Obviously this isn't a problem with
ports of tried and tested games, just so long as the port is sufficiently
bug-free, but it's a shame when an original title comes through showing signs
of insufficient play testing and tweaking. For exampleNapalm was a damn good
RTS, but a few more weeks of thorough testing and tweaking would have
eradicated a number of tiny but disproportionately frustrating omissions. 

Cheers, 

Andrew Korn

