>across the screen and not always going down the full length of the screen.
>It never crashes the game just causes this annoying corruption. Doesn't
>seem to be a problem unique to 3D either as it only happens when I have the
>bitmapcache on so with it on I might get this corruption even after opening
>yam on another screen (so I generally have it switched off till I need it
>for warp3d). Anyone else experienced this problem and if so any cures like
>another cooling fan or something like that ?

Finally somebody else has this problem, too... I have (had?) this problem
for a long time, and IMHO this problem might be very similar to the
mysterious LR-crash problem, which is currently discussed in the newsgroups.

I noticed these errors mostly in W3D-Descent, but also in lots of
those StormMesa demos. In most of the times they only happen with
3d acceleration, but I saw them even sometimes when the CPU itself
did the painting.

I did quite a lot of analysis concerning this problem and tracked the
problem down as much as possible. It turned out, that these corruptions
are simple bit errors, as every n-th bit in a 64-bit-block is occasionally
turned from 0 to 1 (never reverse), which then results into vertical
dotted lines which have equal distance in horizontal direction. I even
believe, that the bit number was always the same, but I'm not sure
anymore. The problem has a much higher likelihood if the 3d chip draws
the graphics as if the CPU does it, which also indicates, that the
intensity of the VRAM accesses has a high importance here. Memory
access intensity also seems to be a factor for the other problem
concerning LR-crash (BTW, the LR-crash problem has been solved using
a work-around which is likely to be released soon).

In the last time I never saw these corruptions anymore here, maybe
the cooling situation has become better by continously rearranging
all the stuff inside my tower. Or maybe there was a mechanical problem,
too.

So I have no definite solution how to solve the problem and I also
don't know the actual reason for these problems. It looks like either
a memory or a bus problem (for example if one channel inside a 64 bit
bus tends to be unreliable, which would explain, why always the same
bit in a 64 bit block is corrupted)

bye
