I hope you have done a fair comparison. If you run the MPEG in a window
on your workbench using ISISPPC then the animation certainly looks a lot
better than when you run an MPEG file at fullscreen, where the pixels get
large. Remember, the MPEG movie has a really low resolution, so if you
choose some large screen mode then the animation is simply scaled (with
filtering applied). Try running WO2097 in a small window and then again compare
the results. Or look at the WO2097 movie from a larger distance, which is the
same as looking at an MPEG animation running in a small window.

You also didn't say anything about the resolution used when playing the
movie using IsisPPC.

Speed: I'm basically sure that you won't find any MPEG player which plays
MPEG movies in fullscreen mode at the same speed than the WO2097-player,
when talking about higher screen resolutions (if you selected 800*600 in the
setup requester, then the MPEG movie is running on a 800*600 screen).
That's due to the hardware scaling feature, which is done with Warp3D. For low
screen mode resolution other players might be faster, but don't forget, that
external MPEG players can't simply be used inside an application, and
additionally there aren't too many WarpUp-based MPEG players around.

On the PC developers don't have to worry about MPEG playing, it simply works,
as appropriate libraries are always present, because they are integrated into
the OS. On the AMIGA we have to live with the situation, that tasks like MPEG
playing are not a standard feature, but only available through third party
products, which very often have problems, too (wasn't there a discussion about
MPEG player problems here recently?)

