Please everyone: always say what kind of crash it is. It is something very
different whether the application throws an exception or whether the whole
system freezes.

> Sam Jordan, what makes my machine hang with max mb of texturemem and not 
> with 2,500 MB texturemem ?

Aha, 'hang', indicates a freeze problem...

Well, if your system freezes from time to time, then it can be everything,
including heating problems, maybe larger textures result into more hardware
activity. I really don't know. As we can not count on any reliability
concerning all those modern hardware components it is very often impossible to
say whether a software error or a hardware failure causes a problem. It is
also a pain for the developers, as they often don't know whether a fault is
their fault or the hardware's fault.

On my system I didn't get any crash or complete system freeze with the
production release up to now, always with full texture memory (although I
have to say that the situation here has become much better concerning
hardware reliability, as I also don't get the vertically dotted lines
anymore). I once got an application hang-up, but which let the system alive,
but seeing how many times I have played the game it is (at least for me) not
significant. Some small percentage of stability problems are probably always
there, seeing the many hardware problems people have (heating problems, bit
errors etc.), seeing the problems with the dual processor architecture (caches
etc.), seeing the many dependencies of external software components, which
again aren't integrated well into the OS and have to rely on hacks, which
aren't too reliable. The integration of W3D for example is far from what I would
like to see (hopefully the next OS updates will improve the situation) and the
locking concept of the RTG systems is another big problem, too, as problems
inside locked state often result into complete system freeze.

We will have to live with this until Amiga-OS is improved and goes towards other
hardware platforms (for example POP platform).

bye

