And I hope that my english concerning hardware details isn't too bad here...

I guess it's a mechanical problem. We had this all the time at cologne,
the computer did never boot, when we came back the next morning.
Our machine was a 4000T, so the accelerator is basically in a vertical
position, while the graphics board is horizontal, at the bottom end
of the accelerator card. The CPU slot is at the top end of the accelerator
card.

If you apply some physics formula (or just use some common knowledge)
then you will find out, that the graphics board 'pulls' the accelerator
board out of the slot (provided that those 2 bolts at the top don't fit well
either, which is quite likely as you can't see if they really fit) . In our
case the slot was probably already quite in a bad state, so that with time
the contact gets worse and worse and finally the machine doesn't start
anymore, and we also had the constant LED flashing all the time.

You can either try to press the boards into the slot with a bit more
power, or you can alternatively try to flip the tower to horizontal
position (that was the reason why our tower was flat on the floor,
it really helped). If the situation gets better, then it indicates
that the theory of the mechanical problem might apply.

