I was more looking at the subject... additionally I guess that all those
*big* projects will support triple buffering, it's not difficult to
implement.

A little note: although triple buffering usually doesn't require
synchronisation, it should nevertheless be added. Of course, not the same
algorithm than for double buffering, as it would defeat the purpose of
triple buffering. I mean, it is possible to write a synchronisation code,
which keeps the advantages of triple buffering, but at the same time makes
sure, that the frame rate doesn't exceed the vertical refresh frequency.

Although this scenario isn't important today, it might become important
in future, if hardware becomes faster.

I have implemented such a sync code into my new project, and it seems to
work fine. If anyone is interested I can give more infos and code
fragments.

BTW, the triple buffering algorithm in WO2097 doesn't have such a sync
code (not necessary if fps limitation is enabled). If 320*240*16
triple buffering is selected and fps limitation is disabled, then the
copyright/start screens flicker, because the images are refreshed faster
than the vertical refresh.

