> > every AMIGA so far. We optimized the engine a lot, parts of it
> 
> a 240 603 + PermII beats a voodoo1, but we'll skip pass this advocacy.

There is no point in simply compare the hardware components for itself.
You have to compare the performance of the whole computer. And if you
do that then the above PC still beats every AMIGA so far (when talking about
3d accelerated games). Bus performance is an essential point for complex 3d
applications, and having a L2 cache or not having a L2 cache also makes quite a
difference (especially for WO2097, which deals with huge amount of memory all
the time!). Not to speak about the low memory performance of 603e systems, and
even the memory performance of 604e systems is AFAIK not really top-notch. IIRC
copy performance is about 50-60MB/s (plain read and write performance doesn't
say much). Finally speed is also lost on AMIGA due to frequent cache flushes
and also due context switches, which cost some milliseconds at least. All these
factors sum up and cause a signficant performance degradation.

> dont forget to tweak your gfx card settings! the framerate is tied to the
> vertical refresh rate....so if you're set to 70Hz, you'll get a max
> framerate of 35fps in most cases.

No, that's wrong. If you select triple buffering, then the framerate is
identical to the theoretical frame rate. This even applies to window mode,
because no sync is done there. Only double buffering uses synchronisation
to cleanly switch the buffers.

Besides that I think that WO2097 becomes quite unplayable at 35fps, it wasn't
designed for such high frame rates.

bye

Sam Jordan
