Hi,

On Sun, 28 Nov 1999, fRaC^tioN wrote:
> can ne1 here explain me in short terms how lightmapping (in OpenGL & Warp3D
> if they got different concepts..) is exactly working (or where to find
> information about that?)?

Try www.gamasutra.com, and look through the archives, they had an article
about lightmaps. A very good article can be found on
http://members.home.com/milod, under game tech (in Color and lighting).


Basically, it's a second texture that is applied to the
same triangle in a special way, namely the texture values are multiplied.
A special blending mode is normally needed, which isn't available on any
Amiga board, but the "normal" alpha blending (source, 1-source) can also
be used with monochrome lightmaps. The topic is very complex, but the
Gamasutra article explains it rather well..

> Do i have to calculate these ones (the lightmaps) for every polygon online &
> load 'em up to gfxmem (can't believe that, what a loss of bandwidth)? But
> how should it work then, u have to have different lightmaps for the same
> texture if u tile them over a bigger surface... or am i totally wrong
> here...

Normally, lightmaps are precalculated (and in QMap, you don't have dynamic
lights). You'll either draw them in a second pass, or you can build the
textures in a cache. There are other difficulties involved here, for
instance a texture may repeat on a polygon, but a lightmap is always
intended to be stretched over the whole polygon. Look at this Color and
lighting stuff, it even has some code in it..

