Hi fRaC^tioN

> does in any way...) but i see no possibility to draw bigger surfaces with
> repeated textures and steched light(alpha-)maps in one pass i.e. give the
> texture and the alphamap different u/v-coordinates... u know help (a
> second pass is NOT what i want to hear ;)

For Quake you could theoretically split all surface polygons along the grid
lines of the lightmap and use vertex lighting for the resulting polys. But
this algorithm would be very complex (could be precalculated though).

The main problem is that this would also increase the per frame polygon count
tremendously. For most modern chips the polygon throughput is more critical
than fillrate (on Amiga both aspects are critical :().
But a low fillrate can be compensated by using lower resolutions, a high
polygon count can't.

The QMap software renderer uses a surface cache (sourcecode is included in 
the QMap archive on Aminet). But I doubt it makes sense to use this for 
hardware rendering, the VRAM uploads will kill the performance.
So I fear two-pass rendering is the only feasible solution.

Kind Regards

Peter Annuss

